<h2 id="a082456" class="entry-title"><a href="http://blog.makezine.com/archive/2010/11/smartphone_binder_clip_tripod_mount.html">Smartphone binder clip tripod mount</a></h2>

<span class="mt-enclosure mt-enclosure-image" style="display: inline;"><a href="http://blog.makezine.com/clip-cell-mount.png"><img alt="clip-cell-mount.png" src="http://blog.makezine.com/assets_c/2010/11/clip-cell-mount-thumb-340x536-59353.png" width="340" height="536" class="mt-image-none" style="" /></a></span>

<p>Thanks to maker DannyBR, with the addition of a quarter-inch hole, the ever useful binder clip has acquired a new talent: smartphone tripod mount. [via <a href="http://www.lifehacker.com.au/2010/11/diy-binder-clip-as-mobile-phone-tripod-mount/">LifeHacker</a>]</p>

<blockquote>I was looking for an economical solution to mounting my mobile phone on a table top tripod I have. After watching people come up with elaborate harnesses for their phones, it hit me. I use the largest binder clip I have and drilled a hole in the centre. Afterward, I can easily clamp my phone. My phone has a rubber case around it that will protect it, but I plan on buying some foam tape to place on the edges of the clip so it won't scratch it.</blockquote>




<div class="asset-meta">
<p class="nfo">Posted by <a href="http://blog.makezine.com">Adam Flaherty</a> |
Nov 30, 2010 04:00 AM <br />
<a href="http://blog.makezine.com/archive/cellphones/">Cellphones</a>, <a href="http://blog.makezine.com/archive/hacks/">hacks</a>, <a href="http://blog.makezine.com/archive/iphone/">iPhone</a>, <a href="http://blog.makezine.com/archive/photography/">Photography</a> | 
